Palp: Cymbium with projection (
Fig. 5A
); prolateral side of paracymbium unpigmented and unsclerotized, with numerous setae and spines at tip (
Fig. 5A
); contrategulum with denticulate margin (
Fig. 5A, D, G
); tegulum with serrate marginal apophysis and lamella-shaped terminal apophysis in retrolateral view (
Fig. 5C, F
); conductor situated ventro-proximally on embolus, with proximal portion relatively narrow, and distal portion with one apical spine (
Fig. 5B, E
); embolus with flat opening (
Fig. 5A, D
).

Female genitalia: Median pair of receptacular clusters along anterior margin of bursa copulatrix with long genital stalks, smaller than lateral pair; lateral receptacular clusters with obscure genital stalks, situated slightly dorsolaterally; posterior part of genital area trapezoid (
Fig. 5H, K
).

Variation. Males and females vary in body size. The range of measurements in males as follows ( N = 2): BL 10.00–10.17, CL 4.60–4.61, CW 4.20–4.22, OL 4.83–5.10, OW 3.56–3.85; females ( N = 13): BL 7.91–14.51, CL 3.88–6.06, CW 3.32–5.73, OL 3.62–7.64, OW 2.22–6.43. In addition, female genitalia shows slight intraspecific variation: the diameter of genital stalks of the median pair is different; four receptacular clusters relatively large (
Fig. 5I , L
); or the median pair of receptacular clusters with relative vertical genital stalks; posterior part of genital area arc ( Fig. 5J, M ).
